The &#039;Big &#039;Ol String method&#039; is actually a really interesting one, ive been meaning to blog on it as it appears that it exposes an issue in MSSQL with query plan efficiency on large queries. What makes this scenario particularly interesting is that when you have under 250 statements this performs really well and when you go over 250 statements there is a massive spike (ie 250 statements executes in ~160ms and 251 statements takes over a second) in the time SQL takes to generate a query plan. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
There&#039;s some really interesting answers around this issue on StackOverflow: http://stackoverflow.com/q/10314528/1070291 and http://stackoverflow.com/q/8635818/1070291&lt;br /&gt;
